Description: Limestone relief fragment: this fragment bears part of the prenomen and most of the nomen of Merenptah (deeply incised). The fragment is well preserved apart from the left edge which is much worn near the break. There are no traces of colour.
Curator's comments: It possibly originates from Nabesha where Griffith records a limestone block with the name of Merenptah built into a tomb (W. M. F. Petrie, 'Nabesheh' (London, 1888), 31 in 'Tanis' II).
Bibliographic references: Bierbrier 1982 / Hieroglyphic texts from Egyptian stelae, etc., in the British Museum, Part 10. (pl.24)
Condition: Fair; (incomplete). The fragment is well preserved apart from the left edge which is much worn near the break.
